            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.XV.R6</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Open at the chief Butler&rsquo;s</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-52cd3135-7fff-a28e-d3dd-20c965744f25\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Although we might read &ldquo;Open&rdquo; as an imperative verb, this note is likely descriptive rather than proactive, since all the right-hand notes were likely retroactive (see LD.XV headnote annotation). The chapter indeed opens with &ldquo;the newly-married pair&rdquo; being &ldquo;received by the Chief Butler&rdquo; (LD 592). The possessive Dickens employs in this note indicates this unnamed character&rsquo;s condescending presence and the influence he holds over both Mr. Merdle (he described in chapter 12 as &ldquo;the Avenging Spirit of this great man&rsquo;s life&rdquo; [540]) and Mr. Dorrit, who feels himself under the butler&rsquo;s scrutiny at the end of this chapter and in the opening paragraphs of both of the following chapters (LD 598 &amp; 608). The Chief Butler&rsquo;s power over those he ostensibly serves is such that Dickens imagines him in this note as the proprietor of the house itself.</p>"
        }
    ],
